1
00:01:57,229 --> 00:01:59,322
<i>Katie!</i>

2
00:01:59,899 --> 00:02:01,491
<i>Cora!</i>

3
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:03,258
<i>You love your sister?</i>

4
00:02:03,502 --> 00:02:06,027
<i>You make any noise,
you know what happens.</i>

5
00:02:52,484 --> 00:02:54,008
Good morning, Estelle.

6
00:02:54,219 --> 00:02:57,882
- How am I looking, Paul?
- That's better. That's better.

7
00:03:13,770 --> 00:03:15,761
Morning, Mr. Edgecomb.

8
00:03:15,939 --> 00:03:17,236
Some Danish this morning?

9
00:03:17,441 --> 00:03:20,638
No, just two pieces of dry toast,
Hector. Thanks.

10
00:03:20,811 --> 00:03:22,210
Leftover's fine.

11
00:03:22,412 --> 00:03:25,870
- Dry and cold, same as always.
- Cold is better.

12
00:03:27,551 --> 00:03:29,348
Especially on those long walks.

13
00:03:30,888 --> 00:03:31,980
Am I right?

14
00:03:33,557 --> 00:03:37,015
Don't let Nurse Godzilla catch you.
She'll raise holy hell.

15
00:03:37,194 --> 00:03:39,321
We're not supposed to let you
wander off.

16
00:03:42,232 --> 00:03:46,532
Where do you go every day?
What do you do up in those hills?

17
00:03:47,004 --> 00:03:48,631
Just walk.

18
00:03:49,239 --> 00:03:50,796
I like to walk.

19
00:03:53,309 --> 00:03:55,300
You try not to fall down, bust a hip.

20
00:03:55,912 --> 00:03:58,608
I don't wanna be in
no damn search party.

21
00:05:08,149 --> 00:05:12,483
<i>You want this man constantly in your life?
Explain the moral basis of that.</i>

22
00:05:12,687 --> 00:05:13,745
<i>I've made mistakes.</i>

23
00:05:13,955 --> 00:05:16,185
<i>Tony doesn't admit that
he's not a good father.</i>

24
00:05:16,358 --> 00:05:20,225
<i>She can't ask nothing. You can't
ask nothing. I have six kids myself.</i>

25
00:05:22,029 --> 00:05:23,929
Why do we always watch this stuff?

26
00:05:24,732 --> 00:05:26,165
It's interesting.

27
00:05:27,167 --> 00:05:31,536
Interesting?
Bunch of inbred trailer trash?

28
00:05:31,739 --> 00:05:34,299
All they ever talk about is fucking.

29
00:05:34,508 --> 00:05:37,841
<i>- and ain't no way in this green earth
I would have a father like that.</i>

30
00:05:38,012 --> 00:05:42,711
<i>If what you saying is true...
No, I'm talking now. I'm talking now.</i>

31
00:05:42,883 --> 00:05:46,011
<i>- What kind of a mother are you?
- One that causes people more...</i>

32
00:05:46,186 --> 00:05:48,586
<i>- is going to let you try...</i>

33
00:05:48,756 --> 00:05:53,989
<i>- You're dead! You can't come back!
- It's back. The Popeil Pocket Fisherman.</i>

34
00:05:54,161 --> 00:05:56,095
<i>Take my husband, take my kids...</i>

35
00:05:56,263 --> 00:05:58,197
Are you all right?

36
00:05:59,433 --> 00:06:01,924
You look tired. You're not yourself.

37
00:06:02,136 --> 00:06:04,797
No, I'm fine. I promise.

38
00:06:05,204 --> 00:06:08,901
You're wearing yourself out
with those walks every day, I think.

39
00:06:09,108 --> 00:06:11,042
Not that you asked me.

40
00:06:11,377 --> 00:06:14,210
I just didn't sleep well, is all.

41
00:06:15,214 --> 00:06:18,513
I had a few bad dreams. It happens.

42
00:06:18,718 --> 00:06:20,379
I'll be fine.

43
00:06:28,928 --> 00:06:31,522
<i>If Madge doesn't care,
I certainly don't.</i>

44
00:06:31,731 --> 00:06:32,857
<i>Neither do I.</i>

45
00:06:33,666 --> 00:06:35,691
Now, this here is worth a look.

46
00:06:37,537 --> 00:06:39,437
<i>I'm in heaven</i>

47
00:06:40,640 --> 00:06:46,374
<i>And my heart beats so
That I can hardly speak</i>

48
00:06:47,046 --> 00:06:48,979
<i>And I seem to find</i>

49
00:06:49,181 --> 00:06:52,878
<i>The happiness I seek</i>

50
00:06:53,385 --> 00:06:56,354
<i>When we're out together</i>

51
00:06:56,555 --> 00:06:59,547
<i>Dancing cheek to cheek</i>

52
00:07:00,592 --> 00:07:02,423
<i>Neaven</i>

53
00:07:02,994 --> 00:07:05,462
<i>I'm in heaven</i>

54
00:07:06,364 --> 00:07:08,992
<i>And the cares that hung around me</i>

55
00:07:09,201 --> 00:07:11,999
<i>Through the week</i>

56
00:07:12,704 --> 00:07:13,966
<i>Seem to vanish</i>

57
00:07:14,172 --> 00:07:17,266
<i>Like a gambler's lucky streak</i>

58
00:07:21,146 --> 00:07:22,579
Paul, what is it?

59
00:07:25,050 --> 00:07:26,449
My God.

60
00:07:31,690 --> 00:07:33,987
I've got to get out of here.

61
00:07:55,980 --> 00:07:59,438
I guess sometimes the past
just catches up with you...

62
00:07:59,650 --> 00:08:02,744
...whether you want it to or not.
It's silly.

63
00:08:03,154 --> 00:08:06,487
Was it the film? It was, wasn't it?

64
00:08:07,725 --> 00:08:12,162
I haven't spoken of these things
for a long time, Ellie.

65
00:08:12,363 --> 00:08:13,762
Over 60 years.

66
00:08:13,964 --> 00:08:16,762
Paul, I'm your friend.

67
00:08:21,337 --> 00:08:25,068
I ever tell you that I was a prison guard
during the Depression?

68
00:08:25,275 --> 00:08:27,140
You've mentioned it.

69
00:08:28,011 --> 00:08:30,502
Did I mention that I was
in charge of death row?

70
00:08:30,713 --> 00:08:32,943
That I supervised all the executions?

71
00:08:37,520 --> 00:08:42,048
Usually, death row is called
"The Last Mile."

72
00:08:42,392 --> 00:08:44,860
We called ours "The Green Mile."

73
00:08:45,562 --> 00:08:48,588
The floor was the color
of faded limes.

74
00:08:49,465 --> 00:08:52,093
We had the electric chair.

75
00:08:52,602 --> 00:08:54,331
"Old Sparky," we called it.

76
00:08:56,739 --> 00:08:59,572
Oh, I've lived a lot of years, Ellie...

77
00:09:00,376 --> 00:09:04,209
...but 1935, that takes the prize.

78
00:09:05,547 --> 00:09:07,378
That year, I had...

79
00:09:07,549 --> 00:09:10,780
...the worst urinary infection
of my life.

80
00:09:12,487 --> 00:09:13,920
It was...

81
00:09:14,957 --> 00:09:17,221
It was also the year of...

82
00:09:17,726 --> 00:09:19,921
...John Coffey...

83
00:09:21,063 --> 00:09:23,497
...and the two dead girls.

84
00:10:18,185 --> 00:10:20,312
All right, now, hold on!

85
00:10:25,159 --> 00:10:26,456
Up on the tower!

86
00:10:26,627 --> 00:10:27,924
New prisoner's coming in!

87
00:10:28,095 --> 00:10:31,758
You men down in the yard,
step off the fence! Clear that gate!

88
00:10:38,571 --> 00:10:40,095
Put me through to E Block.

89
00:10:54,087 --> 00:10:55,520
E Block.

90
00:10:55,956 --> 00:10:57,287
Yeah.

91
00:10:57,757 --> 00:10:58,985
Right.

92
00:11:20,045 --> 00:11:22,411
Paul? Prisoner.

93
00:11:22,614 --> 00:11:24,206
Christ, give me a minute.

94
00:11:29,788 --> 00:11:31,016
You all right in there?

95
00:11:33,692 --> 00:11:37,628
For a man pissing razorblades, yeah.

96
00:11:52,111 --> 00:11:54,511
You should've took the day off
to see the doctor.

97
00:11:54,713 --> 00:11:57,443
With a new arrival?
You know better.

98
00:11:58,050 --> 00:11:59,540
Besides...

99
00:12:00,052 --> 00:12:03,543
...it's not as bad as it was.
I think it's clearing up.

100
00:12:06,190 --> 00:12:08,488
- All right. Let's look alive, Dean.
- Yes, sir.

101
00:12:15,900 --> 00:12:17,094
Damn.

102
00:12:18,403 --> 00:12:20,394
They're riding on the axle.

103
00:12:30,014 --> 00:12:31,447
What'd they do?

104
00:12:32,250 --> 00:12:33,444
They bust the springs?

105
00:12:42,193 --> 00:12:43,751
Dead man!

106
00:12:44,529 --> 00:12:46,190
Dead man walking!

107
00:12:47,597 --> 00:12:49,929
We got a dead man walking here!

108
00:12:50,767 --> 00:12:53,258
Jesus, please us,
what is he yelling about?

109
00:12:56,139 --> 00:12:57,766
Paul...

110
00:12:58,442 --> 00:13:01,377
...you might reconsider getting
in the cell with this guy.

111
00:13:01,578 --> 00:13:03,011
He's enormous.

112
00:13:03,213 --> 00:13:05,181
Can't be bigger than you.

113
00:13:15,659 --> 00:13:16,990
Dead man!

114
00:13:17,661 --> 00:13:19,322
Dead man walking!

115
00:13:19,529 --> 00:13:20,996
Dead man!

116
00:13:21,531 --> 00:13:22,725
Dead man walking!

117
00:13:23,800 --> 00:13:25,893
Dead man walking here!

118
00:13:27,170 --> 00:13:28,467
Dead man!

119
00:13:32,141 --> 00:13:35,008
We got a dead man walking here!

120
00:13:35,544 --> 00:13:36,806
Dead man walking!

121
00:13:38,881 --> 00:13:42,373
- We got a dead man walking here!
- Percy.

122
00:13:43,085 --> 00:13:44,347
That's enough.

123
00:14:07,543 --> 00:14:09,977
Am I gonna have any trouble
with you, big boy?

124
00:14:15,050 --> 00:14:16,142
Can you talk?

125
00:14:22,056 --> 00:14:25,719
Yes, sir, boss. I can talk.

126
00:14:34,302 --> 00:14:36,827
Move your ass. Let's go.

127
00:14:37,372 --> 00:14:38,737
Come on.

128
00:14:44,045 --> 00:14:45,910
Percy...

129
00:14:46,481 --> 00:14:49,143
...they're moving house
down in the infirmary.

130
00:14:49,717 --> 00:14:52,652
Why don't you go see
if they could use some help.

131
00:14:53,388 --> 00:14:55,049
They got all the men they need.

132
00:14:55,723 --> 00:14:57,350
Why don't you just go
and make sure.

133
00:15:00,228 --> 00:15:03,890
I don't care where you go, as long as
it's not here at this very moment.

134
00:15:08,168 --> 00:15:09,465
All right.

135
00:15:22,482 --> 00:15:24,712
God, you bust my finger.

136
00:15:24,918 --> 00:15:27,318
I wiped that grin off your face,
didn't I?

137
00:15:27,521 --> 00:15:30,957
Goddamn it, Percy,
get the hell off my block!

138
00:15:42,803 --> 00:15:43,929
Fuck you, Percy.

139
00:15:44,137 --> 00:15:47,367
We'll get that looked at, Del.
In the meantime, you stay quiet.

140
00:15:48,107 --> 00:15:50,473
Yeah. Yeah.

141
00:15:54,046 --> 00:15:56,708
I let Harry take those chains off you...

142
00:15:57,283 --> 00:15:58,545
...you gonna be nice?

143
00:16:15,701 --> 00:16:17,225
Your name is John Coffey.

144
00:16:17,637 --> 00:16:19,229
Yes, sir, boss.

145
00:16:19,472 --> 00:16:22,930
Like the drink,
only not spelt the same.

146
00:16:23,309 --> 00:16:24,742
Oh, you can spell, can you?

147
00:16:25,578 --> 00:16:28,342
Just my name, boss.

148
00:16:29,081 --> 00:16:31,446
J-O...

149
00:16:31,883 --> 00:16:33,817
My name is Paul Edgecomb.

150
00:16:34,753 --> 00:16:37,517
If I'm not here, you can
ask for Mr. Terwilliger...

151
00:16:37,722 --> 00:16:40,816
...Mr. Howell or Mr. Stanton.
These gentlemen right there.

152
00:16:43,328 --> 00:16:44,488
Questions?

153
00:16:45,230 --> 00:16:47,630
Do you leave the light on
after bedtime?

154
00:16:50,335 --> 00:16:53,827
Because I get a little scared
in the dark sometime...

155
00:16:54,506 --> 00:16:57,100
...if it's a strange place.

156
00:17:01,946 --> 00:17:05,973
It stays pretty bright around here
all night long.

157
00:17:06,184 --> 00:17:08,778
We always keep a few lights burning
out in the corridor.

158
00:17:09,888 --> 00:17:11,879
The corridor?

159
00:17:13,458 --> 00:17:14,891
Right out there.

160
00:17:43,053 --> 00:17:44,611
You can sit.

161
00:18:06,909 --> 00:18:09,275
I couldn't help it, boss.

162
00:18:09,579 --> 00:18:12,946
I tried to take it back,
but it was too late.

163
00:18:18,054 --> 00:18:23,185
Dean, take Delacroix to the infirmary,
see if those fingers are broken.

164
00:18:23,393 --> 00:18:25,953
Of course they're broken.
I heard the bones crack.

165
00:18:26,162 --> 00:18:28,960
You hear what he was yelling
when we brought the dummy in?

166
00:18:29,165 --> 00:18:31,190
How could I miss it?
The whole prison heard.

167
00:18:31,968 --> 00:18:33,230
Goddamn Percy.

168
00:18:33,970 --> 00:18:36,905
You'll have to answer
for sending him off the Mile.

169
00:18:37,573 --> 00:18:40,064
I'll chew that food when I have to.

170
00:18:40,376 --> 00:18:44,745
Right now I wanna hear about this new
inmate. Aside from how big he is, okay?

171
00:18:45,348 --> 00:18:47,645
Monstrous big. Damn.

172
00:18:47,849 --> 00:18:49,840
Oh, he seems meek enough.

173
00:18:50,051 --> 00:18:51,814
Is he retarded, you figure?

174
00:18:52,487 --> 00:18:54,921
Looks like they sent us
an imbecile to execute.

175
00:18:55,123 --> 00:18:58,422
Imbecile or not,
he deserves to fry for what he done.

176
00:19:01,997 --> 00:19:04,022
Make your blood curdle.

177
00:19:27,856 --> 00:19:31,985
- What?! For God's sake, what?
- The girls! The girls are gone!

178
00:19:32,760 --> 00:19:35,661
Papa! Papa, look! There's blood.

179
00:19:40,034 --> 00:19:41,797
Oh, my God.

180
00:19:46,574 --> 00:19:51,068
Goddamn it, woman! Get on that phone
now. You tell them we headed west.

181
00:19:51,278 --> 00:19:54,372
You mind what I'm saying!
We headed west!

182
00:19:54,582 --> 00:19:57,016
Central! Are you on the line?

183
00:19:57,218 --> 00:20:01,382
Oh, God, please.
Somebody took my little girls.

184
00:20:12,867 --> 00:20:14,528
Katie!

185
00:20:15,502 --> 00:20:17,060
Cora!

186
00:20:48,101 --> 00:20:49,625
Jesus.

187
00:20:50,603 --> 00:20:52,093
Jesus.

188
00:21:02,948 --> 00:21:04,347
I'll kill you!

189
00:21:08,120 --> 00:21:09,781
I'll kill you!

190
00:21:38,617 --> 00:21:40,244
I couldn't help it.

191
00:21:41,286 --> 00:21:44,880
I tried to take it back,
but it was too late.

192
00:21:48,492 --> 00:21:51,689
Boy, you under arrest for murder.

193
00:21:53,731 --> 00:21:55,255
I interrupt?

194
00:21:56,834 --> 00:21:59,496
Well, I'm just about done.

195
00:22:09,380 --> 00:22:10,642
Hey...

196
00:22:11,215 --> 00:22:13,740
...how's that pretty gal of yours?

197
00:22:14,685 --> 00:22:16,949
Melinda's not so well, Paul.

198
00:22:17,688 --> 00:22:18,916
Not so well at all.

199
00:22:20,758 --> 00:22:22,123
More headaches?

200
00:22:22,727 --> 00:22:25,355
Got laid up with another one yesterday.

201
00:22:25,997 --> 00:22:27,430
Worst one yet.

202
00:22:28,132 --> 00:22:32,090
I'll be taking her over to Vicksburg
next day or so for some tests.

203
00:22:33,069 --> 00:22:35,867
Head x-rays and who knows what else.

204
00:22:36,072 --> 00:22:38,836
She is scared to death.

205
00:22:40,910 --> 00:22:42,901
Truth to tell, so am I.

206
00:22:44,147 --> 00:22:47,048
If it's something they can see
on the x-ray...

207
00:22:47,651 --> 00:22:49,482
...maybe it's something they can fix.

208
00:22:50,453 --> 00:22:52,045
Maybe.

209
00:22:56,259 --> 00:22:57,920
This just came in.

210
00:22:58,128 --> 00:23:00,494
DOE on Bitterbuck.

211
00:23:03,500 --> 00:23:06,025
You didn't come all the way down here
to hand me a DOE.

212
00:23:07,070 --> 00:23:11,473
I had an angry call from
the state capitol about 20 minutes ago.

213
00:23:11,641 --> 00:23:14,007
Is it true you ordered Percy Wetmore
off the block?

214
00:23:14,210 --> 00:23:15,506
It is.

215
00:23:16,412 --> 00:23:19,939
Now, I'm sure you had reason, Paul...

216
00:23:20,149 --> 00:23:23,949
...but like it or not, the wife
of the governor has only one nephew...

217
00:23:24,153 --> 00:23:26,018
...and his name is Percy Wetmore.

218
00:23:26,255 --> 00:23:28,155
Little Percy calls his aunt...

219
00:23:28,357 --> 00:23:31,849
...and squeals like a schoolroom sissy.

220
00:23:33,429 --> 00:23:37,593
He also mention he assaulted a prisoner
this morning out of sheer petulance?

221
00:23:37,800 --> 00:23:40,530
Broke three fingers
on Eduard Delacroix's left hand.

222
00:23:40,769 --> 00:23:43,363
I didn't hear that part.
I'm sure she didn't either.

223
00:23:43,572 --> 00:23:45,472
The man is mean and careless
and stupid...

224
00:23:45,674 --> 00:23:48,541
...and that's a bad combination
in a place like this.

225
00:23:48,711 --> 00:23:51,236
Sooner or later, he'll get
somebody hurt or worse.

226
00:23:51,447 --> 00:23:52,778
Stick with it, Paul.

227
00:23:53,148 --> 00:23:54,740
It may not be much longer.

228
00:23:54,950 --> 00:23:59,511
I have it on good authority that Percy
has an application in at Briar Ridge.

229
00:23:59,687 --> 00:24:02,247
Briar Ridge? The mental hospital.

230
00:24:02,457 --> 00:24:03,788
Administration job.

231
00:24:04,158 --> 00:24:05,489
Better pay.

232
00:24:07,128 --> 00:24:09,187
Then why is he still here?

233
00:24:11,132 --> 00:24:13,396
He could get that application
pushed through.

234
00:24:15,670 --> 00:24:18,901
Hell, with his connections, he could
have any state job he wants.

235
00:24:19,707 --> 00:24:21,368
You know what I think?

236
00:24:23,478 --> 00:24:26,970
I think he just wants
to see one cook up close.

237
00:24:29,884 --> 00:24:33,911
Well, he'll get his chance, then.
Won't he?

238
00:24:34,822 --> 00:24:38,952
Maybe then he'll be satisfied
and move on. In the meantime...

239
00:24:39,494 --> 00:24:42,429
...you'll keep the peace?
- Of course.

240
00:24:43,831 --> 00:24:45,058
Of course.

241
00:24:46,833 --> 00:24:48,095
Thank you, Paul.

242
00:24:52,038 --> 00:24:53,596
Hal...

243
00:24:54,574 --> 00:24:56,667
...you give Melinda my love, okay?

244
00:24:57,177 --> 00:25:01,409
I'm sure that x-ray will turn out
to be nothing at all.

245
00:25:02,783 --> 00:25:04,011
You bet.

246
00:25:30,976 --> 00:25:32,443
Paul.

247
00:25:32,611 --> 00:25:34,374
- Hey, you.
- Hey.

248
00:25:35,047 --> 00:25:36,446
The music too loud?

249
00:25:38,450 --> 00:25:42,113
There's just this empty spot in the bed
where my husband usually sleeps.

250
00:25:44,723 --> 00:25:48,318
He said to tell you he's having
a little trouble with that tonight.

251
00:25:51,797 --> 00:25:53,958
Worried about Melinda and Hal?

252
00:25:54,667 --> 00:25:57,135
Is that what's got you up?

253
00:25:57,303 --> 00:25:59,328
Yeah, that...

254
00:26:00,673 --> 00:26:02,140
...and things.

255
00:26:03,175 --> 00:26:04,665
